\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department responds to two fundamentally different categories of adverse IT events,
 governed by two different policy regimes with two different objectives.
 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 governs operational incidents — unplanned technical failures whose cause is non-malicious and whose resolution requires restoring service.
 The governing objective is speed:
 identify the failure,
 locate a workaround or fix,
 and return County operations to normal.
 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 does not care why something broke.
 Its job is to restore service as quickly as possible.
 Root cause analysis is the exclusive domain of 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and does not begin until the 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 incident is closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Chapter 4 governs cybersecurity incidents — events involving malicious activity,
 unauthorized access,
 data compromise,
 or any Indicator of Compromise as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Identification and Reporting Procedures).
 The governing objective for Chapter 4 is containment and forensic integrity.
 A Chapter 4 response may deliberately extend an outage in order to stop the bleed,
 preserve evidence,
 or prevent further compromise.
 Speed of restoration is subordinate to that objective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
These two regimes are not interchangeable,
 and a technician shall not substitute one for the other.
 If an event involves or is suspected to involve an Indicator of Compromise,
 Chapter 4 shall control,
 and 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 shall automatically subordinate.
 The procedure for that transfer is defined in Section 6.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Incident Commander
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall serve as the Incident Commander for all operational incidents governed by this policy by default.
 The IT Director may designate any Information Operations staff member as Incident Commander for a specific incident.
 The IT Director shall document designations in the relevant work order at the time they are made,
 specifying the scope and duration of the designation.
 Designation authority and decision rights for this role align with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The title Incident Commander is singular.
 No parallel title — Major Incident Manager or equivalent — exists within the ECIO framework.
 This role applies uniformly to both 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 operational incidents and Chapter 4 cybersecurity incidents.
 There is no disambiguation of title between the two contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Incident Commander shall:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Exercise full command authority over the operational response for the duration of the designated incident,
 including technician assignments,
 escalation decisions,
 and communication with external vendors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Direct the Hard Fork transfer to Chapter 4 jurisdiction upon confirmation of an IoC under Section 6.2,
 and coordinate with Chapter 4 protocols as the incident record transitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Determine when to return jurisdiction from Chapter 4 to 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 operational recovery where applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Document all command-level decisions in the incident work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Hard Fork — Indicator of Compromise Discovery and Jurisdictional Transfer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
If a technician working a 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 operational incident discovers,
 at any point during the response,
 any event or condition that constitutes an Indicator of Compromise (IoC) as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 
\series bold
Policy 3.06
\series default
 immediately and automatically subordinates to Chapter 4.
 This transition is not discretionary.
 It shall not require supervisor approval.
 The technician's obligation upon IoC discovery is to act immediately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Upon discovering an IoC,
 the technician shall:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Cease all troubleshooting immediately.
 No further diagnostic,
 remediation,
 or configuration activity shall be performed on the affected system or systems without express direction from the Incident Commander.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Preserve the system's current state.
 The technician shall not power off,
 reboot,
 disconnect,
 or otherwise alter the affected system's physical or logical state,
 except to prevent immediate harm to persons or to prevent active data loss that cannot be addressed by other means — and only then with immediate notification to the Incident Commander of the action taken.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Document the IoC observation in the work order notes immediately.
 The notation shall describe specifically what was observed,
 when,
 and on which system.
 This entry constitutes the initial forensic record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Notify the Incident Commander immediately via the most direct communication channel available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\lang english
Await direction from the Incident Commander before taking any further action on the affected system or the incident work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The work order shall not be abandoned upon Hard Fork.
 It shall transfer jurisdiction.
 The 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


